snippet.textDisplay: BTW: Fluid resistance through a bunch of bends in a system increases the pump pressure needed to flow the system due to the increased 'resistance'. The less squared bends you have, the more flow you will have. Simple fluid-dynamics. I forgot the formula, but every degree=a certain resistance in the circuit based on the fluid type and viscosity. This has nothing to do with its thermal properties, so that is a factor too given the application.

snippet.textDisplay: PCs like this one in the video are cool and powerful for their time and such, but in the past few years I have watched builds like this one (even simpler ones), I have noticed a rather bad trend when it comes to the cases and some other hardware: Appearance over practicality. In other words... These builds look amazing, but they throw the "easy to work on" part out the window, completely. There's a lot of things in them that should you ever need to service for whatever reason, you'll need to disassemble a good chunk of the PC or more, just to get to some specific part, while in a regular case, all you need to do is open the side panel and stick your hand inside the case without having to remove anything else to get to what you need. I am, of course, speaking generally. I've seen "fancy" builds that still manage to look good while being practical to work on, but most I've seen are rather troublesome to do anything inside the case. Those are the kinds of computer that you build and then pray you'll never have to fix anything inside of it. Pray it just works forever until the day it is retired. I don't like this trend.
